04995nam a22008175i 9780823277582DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232775827 a10.1515/97808232775822doi  a(DE-B1597)555315  a(OCoLC)1002193162  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0150002bisacsh04a190.9/052231 aNeyrat, Frédéric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAtopias :bManifesto for a Radical Existentialism /cFrédéric Neyrat. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLit Z00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tCritique of Pure Madness -- tBook I: Toposophy -- tThe Undamaged and the Contagious -- tSaturated Immanence and Transcendence ≈ x -- tSocratic Divergence -- tBook II: Theory of the Trans-ject -- tBeing-Outside -- tCoalitions -- tAb-solved Freedom -- tLanguage and Disjoining -- tOn the Subject of Animals -- tBook III: The Metaphysical Proposition -- tThe Transgression of the Principle of the Excluded Middle -- tThe Leap and the Loop -- tThe Unlocatable -- tThe Madwoman of the Out-of-Place -- tScience(s), Art, Politics -- tWhat Cries Out -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book offers a manifesto for a radical existentialism aiming to regenerate the place of the outside that contemporary theory underestimates. Neyrat calls this outside "atopia": not utopia, a dreamt place out of the world where everything would be perfect, but atopia, the internal outside that is at the core of every being. Atopia is neither an object that an "object-oriented ontology" would be able to formalize, nor the matter that "new materialisms" could identify. Atopia is what constitutes the existence of any object or subject, its singularity or more precisely its "eccentricity." Etymologically, to exist means "to be outside" and the book argues that every entity is outside, thrown in the world, wandering without any ontological anchor. In this regard, a radicalized existentialism does not privilege human beings (as Sartre and Heidegger did), but considers existence as a universal condition that concerns every being.It is important to offer a radical existentialism because the current denial of the outside is politically, and aesthetically, damaging. Only an atopian philosophy-a bizarre, extravagant, heretic philosophy-can care for our fear of the outside. For therapeutic element, a radical existentialism favors everything that challenges the compact immanence in which we are trapped, losing capacity to imagine political alternatives. To sustain these alternatives, the book identifies the atopia as a condition of the possibility to break immanence and analyze these breaks in human and animal subjectivity, language, politics and metaphysics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExistentialism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aExistentialism.  aMetaphysics.  aSocrates.  acoalition.  aexistence.  afreedom.  aimagination.  aimmanence.  aoutside.  atranscendance.1 aHunter, Walt.1 aShaviro, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaviro, Steven.1 aTurner, Lindsay.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823277582zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823277582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823277582.jpg  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  a